Project Foundations for Data Science: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 40

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders¶

In [34]:
#create a function where we are basically telling it that if the order is above 20, do a 25% charge.
#else if (elif), if the order is above 5 dollars, do a 15% charge, and if it doesnt meet any of those conditions, dont charge anything
def calculate(order_cost):
    if order_cost > 20:
        return order_cost * 0.25  # 25% charge
    elif order_cost > 5:
        return order_cost * 0.15  # 15% charge
    else:
        return 0  # No charge for orders less or equal to 5 dollars

#apply the previous function to the column cost of order and save it all in the new dataframe revenue
df['revenue'] = df['cost_of_the_order'].apply(calculate)

#of everything done in the previous step, just add up revenue
total_revenue = df['revenue'].sum()

money = df['cost_of_the_order'].sum()

percentage_of_revenue = (total_revenue / money) * 100


print("Money coming in: $", money)

print("Total revenue generated by the company: $", total_revenue)

print("Of the total money coming in, " , percentage_of_revenue , "% is revenue.")

Money coming in: $ 31314.82
Total revenue generated by the company: $ 6166.303
Of the total money coming in,  19.691325065895317 % is revenue.

Observations:¶

I wanted to make the comparasion of the total money coming in and the revenue generated by the company. Of all the money coming in, roughly 19.69% is revenue. Revenue from the small orders that are below 20 dollars barely generate revenue in comparasion to the bigger orders, so there is a high dependence of orders above 20 dollars.

This could be because of big orders that are for families, groups, hangouts, etc which could take a long preparation time. Another additional factor could be rush hour, traffic, etc. Even so, the percentage is very low which could guarantee a high satisfaction rate.

Observations:¶

I wanted to check the amount of deliveries that are during the weekend in comparasion to during the week. It is clear to see that there are way more orders during the weekend; and because of that, you'd think that the mean delivery time during the week would be less. However, it makes sense for the mean delivery time during the weekend to be less as there could be more drivers readily available to take on the orders.

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Conclusions:¶

  • There aren't to many correlations, but there are patterns. No correlations in the matrix data.
  • The most popular places offer cuisine types of american, japanese, chinese, etc.
  • The highest rated restaurants offered these types of food as well.
  • Weekends are busier than weekdays.

Recommendations:¶

  • Give promotions to promote the orders to be bigger than 20 dollars, as most revenue is generated there.
  • Value your high value customers that are willing to spend more and order frequently.
  • Give very small discounts or do a point reward system to people who commonly give ratings and provide feedback.
  • Give more incentives for the weekdays to have more people, like promotions.
  • Even though weekdays have less orders, delivery times are slower. Work on making delivery times faster so there is a bigger satisfaction rate and people could be motivated to order more during the week.
